# Process Capture

Turns a messy explanation of how your organisation does something into a clean, professional process guide. Works from transcripts, voice note text, rough notes, or just a conversation.

## When to use it

- Use this when someone on the team does something important and it only lives in their head
- Use this when a new staff member or volunteer keeps asking the same "how do I..." questions
- Use this when you need a consistent process documented before a handover or transition
- Use this when you have a recording or transcript of someone walking through how they work and want it formalised
- Use this when you want to hand a process to a funder, auditor, or board and need it to look professional

## How to use it

1. Start a Cowork session and type something like "document this process" or "I want to capture how we do X"
2. Paste in any notes, transcript text, or voice note content you already have, or answer a few questions to get started from scratch
3. Review a plain-text draft and give feedback before anything is finalised
4. Once you are happy, the final files are generated and ready to download

## What you will get back

Two files are produced:

- A **Word document (.docx)** containing the full process guide, including a visual swimlane diagram showing who does what and in what order, a step-by-step procedure, and a quick-reference table
- A **standalone diagram (.svg)** of the swimlane, which you can drop into a presentation or share separately

Both files are named after the process title (for example: `Expense Processing Guide.docx`).

## Good to know

- The more context you can give upfront, the less back-and-forth is needed. A voice note transcript or rough dot points works well as a starting point.
- You will review a draft before any files are created, so nothing is finalised until you say so.
- This skill produces internal operational guides, not external communications or policies. If you need a one-pager for a funder or a policy document for a board, those need a different approach.
